  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Specify the coordination number of cobalt in $$\\left[\\mathrm{Co}(\\mathrm{CN})\\left(\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}\\right)(\\mathrm{e n})^2\\right]^{2+}$$</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "6"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "4"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "0"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "3"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The coordination number of a central metal atom in a complex is determined by the number of ligand donor atoms to which the metal atom is directly bonded. In the complex $$\\left[\\mathrm{Co}(\\mathrm{CN})\\left(\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}\\right)(\\mathrm{en})^2\\right]^{2+}$$, let's analyze the ligands that are bonded to the cobalt ion:</p>\n\n<ul>\n\n<li><b>CN</b> (cyanide) - This is a monodentate ligand, contributing 1 donor atom to the coordination number.</li>\n\n<li><b>H<sub>2</sub>O</b> (water) - This is also a monodentate ligand, contributing 1 donor atom to the coordination number.</li>\n\n<li><b>en</b> (ethylenediamine) - This is a bidentate ligand, meaning each molecule of en contributes 2 donor atoms to the coordination number. Since there are 2 en ligands, they contribute a total of 4 donor atoms.</li>\n\n</ul>\n\n<p>Adding up the donor atoms:</p>\n\n<ul>\n\n<li>CN: 1 donor atom</li>\n\n<li>H<sub>2</sub>O: 1 donor atom</li>\n\n<li>2 en: 4 donor atoms (2 per ligand)</li>\n\n</ul>\n\n<p>Thus, the total coordination number of cobalt in the complex is $$1 + 1 + 4 = 6$$. Therefore, the correct answer is:</p>\n\n<p><b>Option A: 6</b></p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2021,
    "yearKey": "viteee-2021",
    "difficulty": null
  },
